The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – The Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will need to be allocated.
Conditions will have to be put in place.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be disqualifying, but there will be future problems.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident, however, that the country was not ready.
Her fiscal policy was already out of control when she joined the monetary union in 2001, and her unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this answer is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and deep budget deficits, sees Greece as a reflection of its own future.
And if that's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing a little better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek help.
All of this raises a single question: wasn't the real mistake not in creating the euro?
Since I was one of the few Americans who encouraged the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking me: are you now reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If she does nothing, the next crisis could easily make this one look like a walk in the park.
If she wants to complete her monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, members of the Union can only provide assistance to Greece by circumventing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or in circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders offer assistance, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it must be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget in the hands of a specially appointed expert by the administration of President Barack Obama?
In fact, it wouldn't bother them too much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
Public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the state of California as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom these orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do things like this because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant, especially in light of its history during World War II, particularly in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political ties.
Those who have a strong emergency assistance mechanism will really have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The Chancellor of Germany, Angela Merkel's electorate, hates this kind of rescue because they know well who will be responsible for it.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also shares responsibility for this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank, not required to account for its actions, but today this bank has adopted a monetary policy that is excessively expansionary, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The huge current surpluses of Germany worsen their situation.
Moreover, his fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has consequently benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should get her own back.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as the political integration necessary to make it possible.
She must provide more financial support.
Isn't she best positioned to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that will lead Europe toward a more mature political integration.
One can only hope.
